With the web now being so large and surpasing everyones expectations here are some good, and bad things that have
started to appear as a result of the social media boom;

http://socialmediatoday.com/karenn1617/1745751/effects-social-media-how-we-speak-and-write

I think that the article pays too much attention to "text speak" Anyone who's spent more than an hour on the internet
is fully aware of the monsoon of people just waiting to correct your grammar and pull you up if you don't speak properly.
I just think it's a common misconception that all kids speak in "text speak" because in my experience, it's the middle
aged people and people who haven't been brought up with the internet that excesively use text speak.

To put it into context, Both my parents born in the 70's, and grandparents born in the 40's, use social media and they
all use ALOT of 'text speak' whereas my younger relatives like my cousins, born in the late 80's and 90's go to lengths
to make sure they're using proper grammar and spelling. The entire reasoning behind text speak was to make texting on old
mobile phones easier back before every phone had a qwerty keyboard and you had to press the keys multiple times to type
one letter. The irony is, is that most of the kids that are apparently using text speak are too young to have even
experienced that. It's the older generation that were living and breathing the mobile phone boom.

After that little rant, here's another infographic that goes through some of the more positive aspects of social media
and what it helps us to acheive and how we use it.

http://thumbnails.visually.netdna-cdn.com/how-social-media-is-changing-the-world_51eff38e5f0eb_w587.jpg

I think some of the numbers here are pretty staggering, 89% of job recruiters have hired through Linkedin, 4 Billion
videos are watched every day on YouTube, 100,000 tweets are sent every minute. It helps to visualise the sheer scale
and power of the internet.

